The symptoms of Patterson-Stevenson-Fontaine syndrome are present from birth. These symptoms include characteristic facial features and a&nbsp;<a href="https://rarediseases.org/rare-diseases/split-handsplit-foot-malformation/">split-foot deformity</a>. The characteristic facial features are known as&nbsp;<a href="https://www.ucsfbenioffchildrens.org/conditions/mandibulofacial_dysostosis/">mandibulofacial dysostosis</a>&nbsp;and may include a recessed jaw (<a href="https://medlineplus.gov/ency/article/003306.htm">retrognathism</a>),&nbsp;<a href="https://medlineplus.gov/cleftlipandpalate.html">cleft palate</a>, and changes in the features of the external ears. In some cases, people with this syndrome have been known to have some&nbsp;<a href="https://medlineplus.gov/ency/article/003044.htm">hearing loss</a>. A split-foot deformity (ectrodactyly) may include absence of the toes<a href="http://www.childrenshospital.org/conditions-and-treatments/conditions/cleft-foot/symptoms-and-causes">, clefts in the feet</a>, and fusion of toes together (<a href="https://medlineplus.gov/ency/article/003289.htm">syndactyly</a>).[10682][10681]&nbsp;<br />
<br />
Some people with Patterson-Stevenson-Fontaine syndrome may have all of these features, while others may only have features affecting the face or feet.[10682]&nbsp;
